    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I'm looking at this specific clause right now in an NDA I'm about to sign, though. It's about \"indemnification\" and it sounds pretty intense. Could you break down what this part means in plain English?\n\n\"The Consultant shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Client from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, deficiencies, claims, actions, judgments, settlements, interest, awards, penalties, fines, costs, or expenses of whatever kind, including reasonable attorneys' fees, arising out of or occurring in connection with any third-party claim related to a breach of the Consultant's representations or warranties under this Agreement.\"",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In plain English, this clause means the Consultant agrees to pay for and fight any legal battles or financial losses the Client suffers if the Consultant breaks their promises or guarantees made in the agreement. Essentially, if a third party sues the Client because the Consultant did something wrong or lied about their services, the Consultant must cover all costs, including legal fees, up to the point of judgment or settlement. This is a significant risk because it places the entire burden of liability for the Consultant's failures directly on them, even if the Client had to initiate the lawsuit. You should carefully consider if this level of protection aligns with the services you are providing and whether you have the financial capacity to absorb such potential costs.",
      "source": "target",
