    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for explaining that. it sounds pretty scary tbh. are there any specific ways these kinds of clauses can be \"sneaky\" or have hidden traps that might catch someone off guard? like, what should I be looking out for that isn't immediately obvious?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, there are many hidden traps in indemnification clauses that can catch you off guard, often requiring a fine-toothed comb to spot. One common sneaky element is the lack of a \"reasonable cause\" defense, meaning you might be liable even if you couldn't have reasonably foreseen the breach. Another trap is the scope of \"connections,\" which might define \"arising out of\" so broadly that it covers claims unrelated to the contract entirely. Additionally, clauses often omit a cap on liability, exposing you to unlimited financial damage, or they might include broad categories like \"consequential damages\" that could include lost profits or business interruption. Always look for these hidden limits and definitions to ensure your exposure is actually manageable. If any of these seem too broad, consider negotiating to add a specific cap or a list of what is excluded before you sign.",
      "source": "target",
